solutions.Solution 4 (Graphing):
If we graph $\sqrt{x^2+y^2}=x+y,$ then we get the union of:


\begin{itemize}
\item positive $x$-axis
\end{itemize}
\begin{itemize}
\item positive $y$-axis
\end{itemize}
\begin{itemize}
\item origin
\end{itemize}
Therefore, the answer is $\boxed{\textbf{(D)}}.$


The graph of $\sqrt{x^2+y^2}=x+y$ is shown below.
[asy] /* Made by MRENTHUSIASM */ size(200);   int xMin = -5; int xMax = 5; int yMin = -5; int yMax = 5;  draw((xMin,0)--(xMax,0),black+linewidth(1.5),EndArrow(5)); draw((0,yMin)--(0,yMax),black+linewidth(1.5),EndArrow(5)); label("$x$",(xMax,0),(2,0)); label("$y$",(0,yMax),(0,2)); draw((xMax,0)--(0,0)--(0,yMax),red+linewidth(1.5)); [/asy]
